[h1]Danganronpa: Trigger Happy Havoc (no fire weapons version)[/h1]

Pros:
+ Extremely well written characters engaging in delightful, predominantly grounded dialogues ;
+ Outstanding english voice acting ;
+ Intelligently written and paced narrative that's presented in such a way that the player is rarely left clueless or blindsided ;
+ The looming sense of mystery makes moving forward in the narrative an addicting experience ;
+ A [b]whole[/b] unlockable mode that has the player go through the story in a completely different way ;
+ Zero hiccups, glitches, bugs or crashes.

Cons:
- All gameplay features fall between passable and downright bad ;
- A certain degree of freedom is given to the player in an interesting setting only to then present absolutely nothing that makes exploring that setting worth it ;
- Player agency is very limited, both within and outside of the narrative ;
- A handful of the solutions to the mysteries presented are made fairly obvious well before it ought to have been intended, making some of the characters' reactions feel unnatural or awkwardly slow.

Danganronpa: Trigger Happy Havoc is a visual novel adventure originally release in 2010 for the PSP. The game would see a release on many platforms over the years, arriving to Steam in 2016. Being a visual novel first and foremost, the experience provided by Danganronpa is [i]mostly[/i] a timeless one, hindered mainly by the plethora of gameplay mechanics employed to keep the players engaged. Stemming in Japan's rythm games, assorted puzzle games and visual novels before it, D:THH's gameplay is an anachronistic mess when played on regular difficulty. These features are used to try and convey the atmosphere of a given moment and I can't quite say it fails at that, but it hardly succeeds at anything when it demands from the player to make [i]sometimes[/i] illogical choices and/or hinders the flow of the narrative. A gameplay feature that was seemingly teemed with potential of strengthening the narrative but ultimately falls short at doing so is the exploration sections of the game. It cannot be overstated just how interesting the setting was and how much freedom the player is given only to be met with a profoundly unexciting lack of development around the game's map.

Needless to say, at this point, but D:THH would've been better off [b]not[/b] trying to get one step ahead on the gameplay front. That's especially true when you account for the great cast of characters, the beautifully written dialogues that seem to perfectly complement each character, the mystery surrounding everything and everyone within the boundaries of the game and ultimately, the pace and cleverness of the narrative events where it all comes together so well. I can safely say that I've left a handful of 2 hour long sessions behind feeling like I could go for another two hours of it just over how intrigued I was. I've spent minutes on end at work wondering about the possibilities and sometimes digesting what I had seen on my previous evening of playing the game. It's like everything's presented and paced just so, and one has but to follow through to [b]know[/b]. The game is bountiful like that ; it gives and it leaves you wondering still, willing and wanting to take more. A few select characters are also easily the catalysts for this formula. Without getting into detail, the obligatory name-drop would have to be Monokuma - if you're new to the series, you just won't see it coming.

I found that some things related to the narrative could've been done better, without having let the game down. Firstly, for a game tailored in Danganronpa's fabric it would've been pleasant to give the player some room for error, or perhaps leave something to be missed or found that could potentially alter the way the player perceives any given event. On a limb, I wouldn't have minded being asked to make a decision or two to influence the outcome of things, maybe get a secret ending, or simply learn something I wouldn't otherwise. Ultimately, I'm talking about player agency and replayability relating to the story - D:THH has none. Secondly, many of the events taking place will demand that the player [i]understands[/i] them before the game can keep moving forward. To summarize, perhaps due to how deep seated in logic the game is, you'd have a harder time finding an elephant in a football field than the truth behind some of the events taking place. This isn't particularly jarring considering the things that did bamboozle me and kept me interested and engaged.

When you isolate the narrative aspects of the game, D:THH is a must play for any fan of visual novels and an interesting experience for anyone that's into any fiction or video games at all. Factor in the gameplay aspects of the game and you get yourself a bit of a mixed bag if you're not already an avid fan of visual novels. All things considered, Danganronpa: Trigger Happy Havoc is a game that deserves your time of day. And of course it does. There's a reason why it's a cult classic.

[h1]7/10[/h1]

